headline: Senior Software Engineer at Rhino Partners
summary: I did not choose coding, coding chose me.   As cheesy as it may sound, me becoming a Software Engineer was a total accident. When I was in grade 5, I got my first computer (which I washed with cold water once - RIP). I have been interested in computers and the internet ever since. But I was never interested, or even gave a thought about developing software.  I went through the motions for several years and in 2013 I joined and completed a Diploma Course for Software Engineering just for the sake of it. Even then I was not that interested in software development.  Later, one of my school friends contacted me through Facebook out of the blue and asked if I could help him out with a website he was developing for a client. I had never developed anything in PHP, but I said yes and completed the task with the help of Google.   And then it CLICKED.  That I could do something impactful if I learn this craft. I kind of became obsessed with this idea and I have never looked back. I completed my bachelor's degree in Software Engineering (BEng) at the Informatics Institute of Technology affiliated with the University of Westminster. Then I joined the industry in 2016 as an Intern. I am currently working as a Senior Software Engineer at Explorelogy Private Limited.   I started my development career with Java (Spring, Spring Boot) and related technologies. However, I have had the chance to experience other technologies from the JavaScript world during my time in my current role. I have been working with NodeJS, ReactJS, AWS recently and leaning towards these technologies.

headline: Senior Software Engineer at Allianz
summary: I am a software engineer whom which develops web based full enterprise solution for Dialog, the biggest telecommunication company in Sri Lanka.  How i get here: I was born and raised in Sri lanka, educated in UK and Sri lanka. I quickly adapt to my environment and people around me and that made me a better person and a programmer.  Pivotal movements along the way:  In 2013 : After high school I joined HSBC bank as Executive Customer Service Officer. The first time I was working in a team to achieve one goal. We focused on bringing convenient to our customers on their day to day bank related transactions.  In 2013: While I was working at HSBC I got a Scholarship (Based on my A/L results) to study Electrical and Electronic Engineering In UK. That was a huge opportunity and a adventure. This is where I learned to adapt and see the world in a different perspective. I found my living expenses by working part time at a gas-station as a cashier.   In 2017: I finished my (BE) degree and came back to Sri lanka and got a Job as a Developer at a start up company 'Wtec Lanka' where we developed enterprise application for the local business. Unfortunately the company went under. but I learned not only programming but also needed business strategies to success form our failures.  In 2019: After joining Dialog "OneCrm" team as a full-stack software engineer I was exposed to a whole new world of technologies and devops tools and protocols. This is where I learnt a lot from my colleagues and my supervisors about the BA part of the business and how our work effects the revenue of Dialog. As a programmer I strongly believe having a BA knowledge, will make you a better programmer as well as you will be able to deliver good products to customers.
